Fire services in Cape Town have downscaled operations at Parliament. They are still attending to hotspots on the fourth floor of the National Assembly. Meanwhile, a man will appear in court on Tuesday linked to the fire that engulfed Parliament on Sunday. Courtesy #DStv403 #eNCA CAPE TOWN - A man will appear in court on Tuesday in connection with the fire that engulfed Parliament on Sunday. The 49-year-old was arrested and charged with housebreaking, theft and arson. He will also be charged under The National Key Point Act. READ:Â De Lille: Hawks investigating parliament fire Police say he was caught with suspected stolen property after gaining entry to the parliamentary precinct. The matter has been referred to the Hawks' Crimes Against the State team for further investigation. President Cyril Ramaphosa was at the scene and has commended the Fire emergency services for their swift response. Meanwhile, according to the Head of Architecture at the University of KwaZulu-Natal Lawrence Ogunsanya, Parliament can arise out of the ashes. He says although it's not an easy task, it is possible. Watch the full interview below Head of Architecture at the University of KwaZulu-Natal, Lawrence Ogunsanya, reflects on the history and legacy of the parliament building. Courtesy #DStv403